1. Creating the dataframe, cleaning the data¶

In [2]:
indians = pd.read_csv('diabetes.csv')
#indians.to_csv('exceldata.csv', sep = ';', decimal = ',') for SPSS
for column in indians.columns:
    print((indians[column][indians[column] == 0]).value_counts())

# having 0 blood pressure is irrealistic, also Skin Thickness (it's usually around 23 mm for women)
a, b = indians.Outcome, indians.Pregnancies
indians = indians.drop(['Pregnancies', 'Outcome'], axis = 1).replace(0, np.nan)

indians['Pregnancies'] = b
indians['Outcome'] = a

print(indians['Outcome'][indians['Outcome'] == 0].value_counts()/indians.shape[0])

indians.to_csv('Indians.csv', index = False)

3. Principal component analysis, plotting our results¶

In [4]:
#PCA reduced data:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from matplotlib import rcParams

reduced_data = pd.DataFrame(PCA(n_components = 4).fit_transform(indians.dropna()))
reduced_data.columns = ['PC'+str(i+1) for i in range(4)]
reduced_data['target'] = indians.Outcome
labels = reduced_data['target']
In [5]:
def plotPCA(X, Y, xlabel, ylabel):
    rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 15, 10

    colors = {0:'blue',1:'red'}
    plt.scatter(X, Y, c=np.array([colors[label] for label in labels]))

    plt.title(xlabel + ' vs ' + ylabel)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    
    markers = [plt.Line2D([0,0],[0,0],color=color, marker='o', linestyle='',markersize='12') for color in colors.values()]
    plt.legend(markers, colors.keys(), numpoints=1)

    
    plt.xticks(())
    plt.yticks(())
    plt.show()
In [6]:
#Plot PCA
for i in range(4):
    for j in range(4):
        if i == j:
            continue
        else:
            plotPCA(reduced_data.iloc[:, i], reduced_data.iloc[:, j], 'PC'+str(i), 'PC'+str(j))

print(indians.shape)
for column in indians.columns:
    print(column,indians[column].isna().sum())
    
indians_modelling = indians.dropna()
label = indians_modelling.Outcome
values = indians_modelling.drop('Outcome', axis = 1)
print(indians_modelling.shape)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(values, label ,test_size = 0.1, random_state = 3)

5. Finding the best model according to F-measure confusion matrix¶

In [9]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
#we have an imbalanced data set, so we try to optimize f-measure instead of accuracy (recall's also good)
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score, recall_score

rec = 0
for i in [0.0, 0.001, 0.01]:
    for j in range(1,8):
        for crit in ['entropy', 'gini']:
            dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=3, max_depth = j, criterion=crit, min_impurity_decrease= i, class_weight = {0:0.66, 1: 0.33}).fit(X_train, y_train)
            y_pred = dt.predict(X_train)
            #confusion_matrix_result = confusion_matrix(y_train, y_pred, labels=[1,0])  # Label=[1,0], otherwise predicted and actual axes are swapped
            #print("Confusion matrix:\n%s" % confusion_matrix_result)
            #cv = cross_validate(rf, X_train, y_train, cv=4)
            scoreF = f1_score(y_train, y_pred, pos_label = 1)
            recall = recall_score(y_train, y_pred)
            if recall > rec:
                rec = recall
                fin_model = dt
                print(i, scoreF)
                #accu = accuracy_score(y_test, dt.predict(X_test))
                #print('Accuracy on Test Data:', accu)
                print('Recall:', rec)
                confusion_matrix_result = confusion_matrix(y_test.values, dt.predict(X_test), labels=[1,0])  # Label=[1,0], otherwise predicted and actual axes are swapped
                print("Confusion matrix:\n%s" % confusion_matrix_result)
